Anonymous Mon 29 May 2023 14:06:13 No.56872990 Report
Quoted By:
>>56872683
We agree that composers almost always have to pander by default. A lot of professionals will have to serve a a group of clients. It's the curse of making a career out of your art.

But thankfully we aren't in a professional environment. The artists here are amateurs and the community is small. The fact that you are here considering making art tells me that you may enjoy drawing or writing as a hobby. So the professional composer analogy isn't so relevant.

>And if a good musician doesn't need listeners, how do you know he's a good musician?
My mistake. I phrased this wrong. I meant "good" as in "healthy". Not skilled. Chasing skill is as silly as chasing validation, popularity or money with your art. You no longer call the shots when your art is strongly tied to the opinions of other people. So it's not really yours anymore.

I think your original question was "Why bother posting at all if I'm not supposed to care what the thread thinks?" And my answer to that is,
"Because other people might like your art, but they also might not. You can never control how another person feels. That's why you have to make the art for yourself when you're a hobbyist."
